Can you believe 2022 is almost a wrap? It’s crazy how fast this year flew by! 

As we head into 2023, I’m gonna be doing things a little differently, in an effort to not work 24-7. My poor hubby comes home from work and watches me work until the wee hours of the night, and I have got to stop doing that. So, a few things will be changing as we head into 2023. 

1.  If you message me for help after 5pm EST, you will not get a response until the next business day, after 9 am. Business days are Monday-Friday. Yes, this will affect my Etsy Star Seller status, but my mental health is more important. No one should be expected to work 24-7, 365. So please be mindful of that when you message me. 

2.  I will not be emailing patterns directly to customers. You must download your own purchases via Ravelry, Etsy, or my website. There will be no exceptions to this. I pay fees to these platforms to make my patterns available to you. Sending them directly is a lot of work, and there is also a lot of potential for me to get ripped off by sending them to emails not associated with the buyer. It also means I am paying fees to these platforms, and I’m the one doing the legwork. That’s truly not fair to me. 

3.  If you message me for help, know that I truly am willing to help if I am available. But my first question to you will be “Have you read the pattern notes and the pattern thoroughly?” I work very hard, along with my testers, to make sure I’m writing the easiest to understand directions. I include helpful tips and tricks as your work. So please read through your patterns before getting started, and pay close attention to them as you work. I think you’ll find that I do my best to give you the tools you need to have fun, and easy crochet experience! 

4.  Last, but not least, I will not be answering messages or responding to comments asking what yarn/tag/pom I used in a project. 9 times out of 10, I include all of this info in my posts. If, for some reason, I do not, it’s because I truly don’t know what I used or what supplier it came from. Always click on the post to expand it, and scroll down the bottom to see my supplies listed. 

✌🏼 out 2022!

You may have noticed I haven’t been posting as much lately. Maybe you haven’t noticed, which wouldn’t surprise me, since social media is making it harder and harder for small businesses to be seen. Some days I wonder why I do this. Why I chase my tail. And that’s led me to do some soul searching. Meta taking over Instagram has been a nightmare for makers like me. The pressure to make reels, get verified, post daily, add to your stories 5x a day…it’s tooooo much. It’s a joy sucker. 

While I love what I do, what I don’t love has started to be a bigger part of my daily routine. The constant  chasing my tail, trying to come up with content to post every single day just to be seen by a few, feeling like I just don’t know which direction to go with my business. Removing my patterns from Etsy was a huge step, and hopefully will eliminate a lot of unnecessary stress.  So, I am trying to find a new direction. A new mindset. Going forward, I’m gonna do what brings me joy, without the pressure of constantly trying to be relevant, or without the pressure of living up to stupid star seller status and reviews. I’m going to create and do what brings me joy. If that means I make hooks for fun without feeling like I have to mass produce them, that’s what I’ll do. If that means I write a pattern here or there, not one every few weeks, that’s what I’ll do. And I hope you’ll all stay with me while I figure out the best way to move forward.  When doing what I love starts to feel like a job that never ends, it’s time to switch gears. Who’s tired of the rat race like me? Let’s navigate this bumpy road together!

Have you been on the fence about trying my hooks? Let’s chat!

Over the last 2 years, I’ve worked hard to come up with what I feel are super comfy hooks, not to mention they’re super FUN!  Just like my beanie creations, I love to incorporate lots of color, and glitter almost always has to be a part of my designs. Glitter makes everything better! 

It’s taken a lot of trial and error,  but I am really happy with what has become my signature shape. I love the weight, the feel and the comfy tapered thumb area. If you’re a Bates user, you know how short the shaft it. Because of that, most hook makers leave the thumb rest uncovered. I have never liked how that felt, so on my hooks, you’ll find that only half of the thumb rest is covered. It’s so much comfier! Boye and Clover hooks both have long style handles, for comfort. 

I’ve also done a lot of trial and error with finding the perfect protective coating, and am happy to say I’ve finally found it! ALL of my hooks are coated with a premium resin glaze for durability, and a high gloss shine that will stand the test of time! And don’t forget, each one is hand sculpted with LOVE! I pour my heart and soul into each one! 

Wanna try one? Head over to my website, www.mrsbscrochet.com. There are quite a few beautiful ready to ship hooks available now!

Can we take a minute and have a chat?  This kind of stuff makes me FURIOUS, and sick to my stomach. I saw this ad pop up on my feed, and my blood was boiling!!

Did you know that, unlike knitting, crochet cannot be duplicated by a machine. That means these cute pillows are hand crocheted, most likely by folks in a third world country who are paid pennies on the dollar for their work. Often times, the workers are children, subjected to working 14 hour days in conditions that are horrendous. And, when the trend passes, the leftover items are tossed out. That makes me sick. All of it makes me sick. 

Crocheted items like this are quite popular right now, especially granny square items. Fast fashion is the devil. Mass retailers selling this stuff are not only using and abusing the laborers who make these items, they’re hurting US. Who will buy our handmade items for a fair price if they can go and buy a crocheted pillow for $5.55!??

So what can you do? Boycott these retailers. Don’t buy anything crocheted at mass retailers. Tell everyone you know about this. Encourage people to shop small, and remind them that although our prices are higher, each item is ethically crafted. While we can’t end this garbage, we can tell folks and educate them. Do your part. Share this post. Shout it from the rooftops!

Can we talk?

If you’ve been around me and my page for awhile, you know I’m a huge advocate for mental health awareness. If you’re new here, let me share my story…I’ve battled anxiety and depression for a huge portion of my life. At times, it’s been crippling. I’ve lost a lot of friends because they don’t want to walk this journey with me, and that’s ok. It’s a hard path to be on, and not everyone is equipped to love people through the tough times. My circle is pretty small and very tight, and I’m forever thankful for those that choose to accept me, and my many flaws, and still love me anyway. I have good days, and not so good days. I’m forever thankful to the folks who love me, even on those not so good days.. 

With an uptick of suicides in the news lately, I just wanted to take a moment and remind everyone to be kind. Be compassionate. Don’t alienate folks who struggle with these issues. Not everyone is blessed with the support system that I have. Some folks feel so alone, so beat down by weight of their illness, they lose sight of hope. A kind word, a gentle hug, or just a smile can make the biggest difference to someone struggling. As the saying goes, everyone you meet is battling something, so just be kind.  Give a stranger a compliment, pay it forward at the drive through, or hold the door for a stranger at the store. These small acts of kindness could do a world of good in a world that has seemingly lost sight of how we should treat others. It could turn someone’s horrible day around, and give them hope. 

If you struggle, know that there are people who care. People who don’t think you’re weird, crazy, or useless. If you’re struggling with thoughts of self harm, please don’t be afraid to call 1-800-273-8255  or simply dial 988. 🩷
